<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-300-447  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 300 447.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Jan 23 1989 v6 n3 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus threat mandates legislation, stiff penalties. (ComputerFraud and Abuse Act) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>DiDio, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Laws are presently on the books that make it a crime to knowinglygain access to any government computer without properauthorization.andP;  It is unlawful to impede a compter's ability tofunction and it modify, destroy or disclose information obtainedfrom unauthorized entry.andP;  These laws are written so that the worstoffenders can escape punishment.andP;  Representative Wally Hergerintroduced a revised version of his Computer Virus Eradication Acton Jan 2, 1989 when the 101st Congress re-convened.andP;  Criminalpenalties of up to 10 years in prison and commensurate fines forintroducing a computer virus into a computer system or softwareowned by another individual without that individual's knowledge orconsent are provided by the bill, which also calls for civilpenalties so that injured parties can recover damages from theperpetrator.andP;  It is the first piece of legislation that makes thewriting of a computer virus a crime punishable by imprisonment andfines.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (analysis).andO;Topic:     Computer VirusesLegislationAnalysisLaw EnforcementCommunications TappingAccess Rights.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>